<http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/bag/2003/06/16/news/dengue.outbreak.in.car
.barangays.apparent.html>

Philippines: Dengue Fever Alert in the Cordilleras
--------------------------------------------------
All provincial health officials in the Cordilleras were alerted over the
possibility of a dengue outbreak in remote barangays of the region. The call
came following reports that at least 20 dengue cases were already confirmed
in remote Paracelis town in Mt. Province, prompting health officials to
contact the Provincial Disaster Coordinating Council (PDCC) to help them in
the conduct of massive fogging activities.
In Baguio, Dr. Cecilia Brillantes, chief of the City Epidemiology
Surveillance Unit (CESU) reported that there was a 500 percent increase in
dengue admissions from Jan to Apr 2003 in several sentinel hospitals in the
city. Some 25 cases of dengue were already confirmed compared to only seven
during the same period last year, she added. Brillantes, however, was quick
to claim that there was no dengue outbreak in the city. Still, health
officials have intensified their fogging and information dissemination
activities. "The CESU is on top of the situation," she said.
On the other hand, the Regional Epidemiology Surveillance Unit (RESU) of the
DOH-CAR also advised the Mt. Province Provincial Health Office to dispatch
health workers from Paracelis to prevent possible dengue outbreak in the
eastern part of the province. The Philippine Information Agency in the
province reported that Dr. Bonifacio Magalong, head of the Bontoc General
Hospital, already had appealed for a massive fogging activity with the PDCC.
Paracelis Mayor Cesar Rafael, however, said that a massive fogging activity
is already being implemented in identified dengue endemic areas to eliminate
the dengue carriers.
Magalong reported that all dengue patients are suffering from different
ailments and are presently confined in the municipal hospital, which is also
undergoing rehabilitation. He also asked the PDCC to help in the monitoring
of medicines directly delivered to local officials but without proper
prescriptions from health authorities. He cited the dangerous practice of
many villagers on stockpiling of medicines at home for so long, thus, even
expired medicines are kept for future use.

