[2]
Date: Sat 21 Jun 2003
From: "Pablo Nart" <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Sun Star, Sat 21 Jun 2003 [edited]
<http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/bag/2003/06/21/news/dengue.outbreak.in.mt.
.province.html>

Philippines: Increase in Number of Cases in Cordillera AR
---------------------------------------------------------
Health authorities have declared a dengue outbreak in Paracelis, Mt.
Province following 107 cases of dengue fever recorded from January to May
this year. The number cases also continue to increase, said Dr. Teresita
Bonoan, director of the Department of Health in the Cordillera
Administrative Region (DOH-CAR).She added that an upsurge in dengue cases
reported was noted last month with 51 out patients and admittance. Poblacion
has the highest number of cases at 81 and clustering in sitios Dagawe and
Banilag is now being implemented, Bonoan added.
No fatality had been recorded but some of the dengue patients, whose ages
range from one month old to 68 years old, are in critical conditions at the
Bontoc General Hospital, DOH-CAR reports said. Those 11 to 20 years old were
the ones mostly affected, it added. Severe headache, joint pains and skin
rashes characterize the disease.
Bonoan said that a team from the Regional Epidemiology and Surveillance Unit
(RESU) had been dispatched in Paracelis in close coordination with the
Provincial Health Office and Mt. Province Provincial Disaster Coordinating
Council. An initial report from the RESU team showed that: "The present
outbreak can be attributed to the onset of rainy days, which signaled an
increase in mosquito breeding sites." The report added that most of these
breeding grounds include artificial containers like uncovered drums, pails
and discarded litters like tins, bottles, coconut shells and tires.
Since the first outbreak in 1998, dengue fever has always been characterized
by health authorities as the "disease that should be watched" and contained
immediately. Paracelis Mayor Cesar Rafael earlier said that a massive
fogging activity has already been implemented in identified dengue endemic
areas to eliminate the dengue carriers.
Paracelis, a fifth-class municipality, has a total population of almost 19
000. With the dengue outbreak occurring in the remote eastern part of the
province, Bonoan expressed hopes that other remote towns in the region would
not suffer from another dengue outbreak. Bonoan said that all provincial,
municipal and barangay health offices in the region were ordered to mobilize
a community clean-up drive for the destruction of breeding sites of the
vector mosquito. She added that the posting of public advisory on dengue
fever and control are necessary.
