[5]
Date: Fri 20 Jun 2003
From: "Pablo Nart" <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Australian Broadcasting Corporation News, Thu 19 Jun 2003 [edited]
<http://www.abc.net.au/news/newsitems/s883068.htm>

Australia: Confirmed Cases in Queensland Now Total 19
-----------------------------------------------------
The Tropical Public Health Unit says it has no plans to enact
legislation against people who are lax about preventing the spread of
dengue fever. The number of confirmed cases in the twin cities has
jumped from four to 19 this
week, and most have been acquired locally.
The director of environmental health, John Piispanen, says he is
getting access to three quarters of the homes he is approaching for
inspections, so there is no need to enact any powers. "We are
supported by legislative background, and EHOs [environmental health
officers] generally are regulators, but we think while we're getting
the support we are getting from the people of Townsville generally we
don't need to progress to that," he said. "It is something we've been
talking about for a long time, but basically while we're getting
access to people's houses and yards it's not something we have to
pursue."

