[7]
Date: Fri 20 Jun 2003
From: "Pablo Nart" <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Xinhuanet, Wed 18 Jun 2003 [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2003-06/18/content_925401.htm>

Myanmar: WHO Calls for Greater Public Involvement in Dengue Control
-------------------------------------------------------------------
YANGON: The World Health Organization (WHO) has called for increased public
involvement in the control and prevention of Dengue Hemorrhagic Fever (DHF),
a life threatening disease occurring in Myanmar intermittently especially in
the northern Mandalay division.
A team of WHO specialists, who visited the division recently, suggested that
this disease could be controlled and eradicated through wider community
participation as done in Central Java, Indonesia, where they have evaluated
the dengue eradication programs, the local Myanmar Times reported in its
latest issue. The experts called for building stronger partnership in the
campaign with the Myanmar Red Cross Society and local and international
non-governmental organizations to achieve more success, based on the
on-going campaign with limited resources. DHF mostly causes death among
children aged under 15 in Southeast Asia including Myanmar and the factors
that contribute to DHF include population increase, urbanization and a lack
of effective mosquito control.
DHF was first detected in Yangon in 1969 and a major outbreak of the disease
followed in 1970, which was confined to Yangon until 1973. The first case in
Mandalay division was detected in 1974 and major outbreaks have occurred in
the division about every four years with the most recent in last year.

